Well, that's no help. ![;.;](//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_cry.gif) There's nothing relevant in the log.

With nothing else to go on, the other approach is to methodically remove mods to find out which one or two are causing the problem. You can remove them one-by-one or try a binary search, which should only take about 6 launches to track down a single-mod issue:

1. Remove half your mods.
2. Try to cause the problem.  

    1. 
    2. If the problem's still there, remove half of the remaining mods.
    3. If it isn't, try the other half.

The crash report shows a memory access error, but doesn't say what's causing it. That could be running out of memory or a mod or stock bug, so we're left at either reducing your memory load by texture quality or removing parts, or removing mods altogether.
